WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.700
Hello, as Hannah said, I'm here to talk about how we measure the effectiveness of these models.

00:00:07.400 --> 00:00:15.900
If you're watching this video sometime later from now, maybe take a look at Hannah's video beforehand that we just saw, Lies.

00:00:16.500 --> 00:00:17.799
There's a fair amount of overlap.

00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:23.100
We kind of use similar data sets and she showed you some things that I'll kind of show you also in a different context.

00:00:24.100 --> 00:00:32.400
So the title of this is like, you know, like doing this is hard and that's a little bit of a reflection of like the development process.

00:00:33.099 --> 00:00:41.200
There are a lot of different ways and R packages you can use to qualify how well your event time model works.

00:00:41.900 --> 00:00:51.900
This is probably why it took us as long as it did to actually get everything fully implemented in tidymodels is I think a lot of the time was just doing a lot of research and figuring out what we should be doing.

00:00:52.500 --> 00:00:54.200
As opposed to like what's out there.

00:00:55.400 --> 00:00:57.900
So, you know, Hannah showed you something similar.

00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:08.599
A lot of times with survival models were more focused on probability predictions, especially the probability of survival as opposed to like the point prediction of like your median survival time.

00:01:08.900 --> 00:01:11.900
And here's an example of three data points like she just showed you.

00:01:12.500 --> 00:01:15.199
Two of these data points had event times of 17.

00:01:15.500 --> 00:01:19.300
The red one here was an event and the green one here was censored.

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:23.099
Then we have another one that went a lot further to 100.

00:01:23.699 --> 00:01:26.199
You can see it's probability curve is a lot higher than the other two.

00:01:27.099 --> 00:01:34.900
And so, you know, a lot of times when we look at these models, we want to look at, you know, not so much like when does the event happen, but along some range of time.

00:01:34.900 --> 00:01:40.800
Like what's the probability that it could happen at any time or the probability that it doesn't happen up until now.

00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:52.900
And so when we go to look at these models, if we're really focused on probabilities, then we might want to make our performance metrics be dynamic in the terms of we want to look at specific time points and see how the model is doing.

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:58.099
And so this is an example where every, let's say, 50 days, we're going to look at how the model works.

00:01:58.099 --> 00:02:09.899
Like does the model perform really well here at this slice of probabilities versus way out here in the tail where there's, you know, fewer events, let's say, late in the time period.

00:02:10.399 --> 00:02:15.000
So we're going to be looking at like time dependent or dynamic performance metrics for these models.

00:02:16.300 --> 00:02:18.199
So Hina kind of went into this.

00:02:19.399 --> 00:02:31.500
What people tend to do in these situations is they take the actual like event time data, like your outcome data, and given a certain what we'll call evaluation time, like that's the time we're going to look at our model performance.

00:02:31.800 --> 00:02:40.000
You can take that data and probably, I'll show you why that probably is there in a second, convert that to a binary indicator at a certain time.

00:02:40.300 --> 00:02:43.500
And the way I think about this is I think about like a package getting delivered to my house.

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:51.600
So, you know, I order something, let's say from Amazon and it's been like a day and the package hasn't arrived yet, but I know it's been at least a day.

00:02:51.600 --> 00:02:56.500
So I know my event time so far is one day, but it's censored right now at one day.

00:02:56.899 --> 00:03:07.800
So, you know, what we can do is we can look at specific time points along there and convert that data point of censored at one day to either an event, a non-event or something else.

00:03:07.899 --> 00:03:08.500
We'll see in a minute.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:14.800
So once we've done that, then people tend to use standard like binary classification metrics to evaluate the models.

00:03:15.100 --> 00:03:21.500
And the two that have mostly stuck in the literature are the Breyer curve and the good old well-known area of the RC curve.

00:03:22.100 --> 00:03:24.699
Breyer curve, I'll talk about it a little bit if you've never seen it.

00:03:24.699 --> 00:03:31.199
It's really like a measure of calibration, like how close are my, how accurate are my probabilities compared to their true values?

00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:39.300
And then the RC curve is more about separation of events versus non-events, which doesn't mean you have to have like very accurate probabilities.

00:03:39.300 --> 00:03:41.899
It's just, they need to be separate between your events and non-events.

00:03:42.899 --> 00:03:46.800
We'll talk about both of these and there's a little bit more details at tinymodels.org.

00:03:48.300 --> 00:03:53.300
All right, so we have three cases that like if we have an evaluation time of tau, let's say, you know, I'm looking at

00:03:54.100 --> 00:03:58.000
packages being delivered and I have a delivery that actually happened at day two.

00:03:58.500 --> 00:04:01.100
Let's say tau is like day three.

00:04:01.500 --> 00:04:05.699
So at day three, if you're evaluating your model, you have to think about three different cases.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:13.600
If the actual time that I have is an event, let's say day two and it's before tau, then we count that as event because it's already happened.

00:04:14.500 --> 00:04:22.500
Now, if my time, whether it's censored or a real data point, like an actual event time happens after tau, like after three days,

00:04:22.700 --> 00:04:25.600
I know it's not an event because nothing has happened either way.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:31.500
But let's say I have, I'm evaluating my model at day three and I have a censored value at day two.

00:04:31.799 --> 00:04:35.700
Now, I don't know if that real event time could have been like 2.1.

00:04:36.399 --> 00:04:37.500
We don't know what the answer is.

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:38.500
It could have been five.

00:04:38.500 --> 00:04:39.500
So we don't know what to do with that.

00:04:39.500 --> 00:04:40.700
It's really ambiguous.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.399
And so what these models do is they basically just discard those data points.

00:04:44.700 --> 00:04:49.799
And so the interesting thing here is we're actually throwing away data because we don't know what the answer is.

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:56.399
And that the amount of data that we have at any given evaluation time as we evaluate these models is going to change.

00:04:56.600 --> 00:05:01.600
And that, as you'll see, has a bit of an effect on how we evaluate the models and the trends that we see.

00:05:02.700 --> 00:05:06.000
So this is a nice little figure sort of demonstrating the same thing.

00:05:06.399 --> 00:05:11.399
Here is, let's say we have a package delivered at day two and then a censored value day four.

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:15.200
If I'm evaluating my model at day one, like nothing's happened to the left of this.

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:17.200
So they're both not events.

00:05:17.799 --> 00:05:21.399
If I'm evaluating at day three, I did have an event here.

00:05:22.299 --> 00:05:26.200
Something happened after three, but we know it at time three, it's not an event.

00:05:26.600 --> 00:05:27.899
And then here's the ambiguous case.

00:05:27.899 --> 00:05:29.000
This one's an actual event.

00:05:29.100 --> 00:05:29.799
Does it happen?

00:05:30.100 --> 00:05:35.200
But this one could have happened anywhere between, you know, these two lines or it could have happened much later.

00:05:35.200 --> 00:05:37.299
So we can't really do anything with that data point.

00:05:38.399 --> 00:05:44.399
Now, one thing we know from like statistics is, you know, generally speaking, we just don't throw away data and think like everything's cool.

00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:49.500
So, you know, we have to think about what the consequences are in terms of measuring performance.

00:05:49.700 --> 00:05:54.600
When we have data that is just eliminated, you know, in this case, for good reason, because we don't know what to do with it.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:02.700
And typically we know that just doing the analysis of those data as if nothing ever happened generally leads to bias.

00:06:02.700 --> 00:06:05.100
And that's a, that's, we've known that for like a long time.

00:06:05.399 --> 00:06:07.299
And so there are a variety of ways you can handle that.

00:06:07.299 --> 00:06:14.000
But the one that people tend to do is they tend to take a causal inference approach and then build what they call a propensity model

00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:23.100
to predict, you know, the probability of that data point being missing and then use that additional score for each data point to weigh their metrics and things like that.

00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:24.500
So this is a pretty well-known thing.

00:06:24.500 --> 00:06:25.700
People do it quite a bit.

00:06:25.899 --> 00:06:28.500
You've probably seen it if you were in the causal inference workshop.

00:06:29.100 --> 00:06:33.000
Now in our context, we're going to do basically, we're going to do that.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:37.399
We're going to estimate the probability of something being censored at a specific time tau.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:41.500
And there's detail at the end if we have time or if we need it.

00:06:41.899 --> 00:06:46.299
But the way that we're going to take a very simple method, it's not informative censoring assumptions.

00:06:46.299 --> 00:06:48.600
We don't think that there are any predictors influencing that.

00:06:48.799 --> 00:06:50.799
We can change that later on in tidy models.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:57.500
But right now we do something that honestly I had never heard of, but apparently it's fairly common called a reverse Kaplan-Meier curve.

00:06:57.899 --> 00:06:58.899
So it's a Kaplan-Meier curve.

00:06:58.899 --> 00:07:06.899
We know what that is, but they just switch the event indicators and it's giving us basically the probability that something is censored up to time tau.

00:07:07.600 --> 00:07:12.700
And so then what we do is we do these things called inverse probability of censoring weights.

00:07:12.899 --> 00:07:16.500
We get that probability for every data point, whether it's an event or non-event.

00:07:16.700 --> 00:07:20.500
We take its reciprocal and we use that as a case weight when we compute our metrics.

00:07:20.600 --> 00:07:21.600
And we'll see that in just a minute.

00:07:22.500 --> 00:07:25.200
The best paper on this is Graf et al here.

00:07:25.600 --> 00:07:28.700
I've read this like five times to just get my mind around it.

00:07:29.100 --> 00:07:32.600
And that's probably the best brief reference we have.

00:07:33.399 --> 00:07:36.100
It's mostly concerned with Breyer scores and that's what we'll talk about later.

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:39.600
So here's an example.

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:41.000
So it's a churn data set.

00:07:41.799 --> 00:07:46.000
I have a 1000 data point validation set.

00:07:47.899 --> 00:07:52.000
And I'm going to look at evaluation times going from about 5 to a little bit over 200.

00:07:52.600 --> 00:07:58.299
And so the coloring here is how many data points are able to be included in the analysis because they're not ambiguous.

00:07:58.600 --> 00:08:04.600
And then the line demonstrates the sum of the weights at every design point or at every evaluation time.

00:08:04.799 --> 00:08:14.600
And you can see that it may be hard to tell from the colors, but the number of data points that I have for analysis drops from 1000 maybe to about 250 once you get around 10.200.

00:08:15.100 --> 00:08:23.299
And then, which is not, I think, uncommon from all the data sets I've looked at, but this trend here is not really a reproducible trend from data set to data set.

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:28.200
But it's interesting because things are pretty stable up until about 100, day 100.

00:08:28.500 --> 00:08:37.900
And then you have a very smaller number of weights, which means there are lower weights with fewer people and then an explosion of them.

00:08:37.900 --> 00:08:49.200
And what happens with propensity score sometimes is if you're inverting a probability that's close to zero, sometimes you get like case weights for like 90 or 100 or something pretty large.

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:50.500
And that's kind of what happening here.

00:08:53.599 --> 00:08:56.200
All right, so the Breyer score, as I mentioned, it's a measure of calibration.

00:08:56.400 --> 00:09:05.700
You can think of it as like root mean squared error, but for probabilities and basic classification, you would take these Y's here or the indicator 01.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:12.200
So if I'm looking at like class one, it would be a one here minus the probability of being in class one.

00:09:12.500 --> 00:09:17.400
So if your model was perfect, the probability would be one, you'd be subtracting one from one and zero.

00:09:17.599 --> 00:09:20.299
So the Breyer score is best at zero.

00:09:20.299 --> 00:09:21.599
That means you have a perfect model.

00:09:21.900 --> 00:09:27.599
And with two classes, the sort of like danger zone of my model is really not all that great is about 0.25 and above.

00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:30.599
So that's just basically for classification.

00:09:30.799 --> 00:09:35.599
In our situation, so we have events and non-events, we're looking at a two class problem.

00:09:36.099 --> 00:09:45.799
And what we do here is we do the same calculation, like a Y equal one here means this event, the probability here would be one minus the probability of surviving.

00:09:46.099 --> 00:09:48.200
So that's what happens when you have an event.

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:50.599
And if it's not an event, it's a zero here.

00:09:50.599 --> 00:09:52.400
And then it's just a survival probability.

00:09:52.799 --> 00:09:54.599
And then these are the case weights I mentioned.

00:09:54.900 --> 00:09:59.500
It's the same calculation, but instead of dividing by n, we divide by the sum of the weights at time tau.

00:09:59.900 --> 00:10:00.200
Okay.

00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:05.000
And that that sum of weights is going to, as you just saw in the last figure, is going to vary over time quiz.

00:10:06.799 --> 00:10:07.099
Okay.

00:10:07.799 --> 00:10:09.200
So how do we do this in tiny models?

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:11.500
Hannah showed you a little bit of this.

00:10:11.500 --> 00:10:15.400
So it's maybe not new, or at least it's not more than 10 minutes new to you.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:26.700
Instead of using predict, what we can do is use augment on our model fit, and I'm going to give it my validation set, and I'm going to do a fair number of evaluation times here just to have nice plots to be honest with you.

00:10:27.200 --> 00:10:35.500
The difference between what augment gives you and what predict gives you is augment will give you the extra columns of the probability of being censored and the case weight.

00:10:35.799 --> 00:10:37.299
So it just appends those two.

00:10:37.500 --> 00:10:40.799
It's another list column, like the one she showed you before that had 24 rows.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:46.900
In this case, it'll have, I think, 225 rows in it because I did a lot of evaluation times.

00:10:47.799 --> 00:10:51.700
And then yardstick has a bunch of metrics that are appended with survival.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
So we have a briar score for classification.

00:10:54.299 --> 00:11:05.200
So if you wanted to do that for survival models, you'd say briar survival, give it the data set, tell it where the predictions are, and then it gives you kind of like the standard yardstick format where it gives you a metric name.

00:11:05.500 --> 00:11:12.599
There's now an allow time field here that says that, you know, 30 days, my briar score is this, which is really low.

00:11:13.099 --> 00:11:15.400
And, you know, I just filtered to show you some.

00:11:16.400 --> 00:11:21.599
Now, so you can look at these and maybe the time points that are most interesting to you and figure out, is my model good enough?

00:11:22.400 --> 00:11:23.000
Where is it good?

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:24.000
Where's it not good?

00:11:24.200 --> 00:11:33.500
If you don't really want to have to think about the sort of dynamic nature of this, the other thing you can do is you can do briar survival integrated, and it basically does airing of the curve and normalizes it.

00:11:33.900 --> 00:11:37.500
And honestly, the value here is not that bad for a briar score.

00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:38.500
It's 0.07.

00:11:39.099 --> 00:11:41.200
It's over near 0.25, which is good.

00:11:41.700 --> 00:11:44.099
What does it look like over time in this particular case?

00:11:44.900 --> 00:11:46.400
Early on, the model does really well.

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:58.000
The score is virtually near zero, and then you see it sort of getting a little bit worse, and it peaks, you know, around 0.25 at time 200, and then it comes down again and gets a little bit better.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:09.000
Like early on, this seems like a pretty reproducible trend across datasets, but you know, where your model may work and not work is going to, again, be dataset dependent.

00:12:11.799 --> 00:12:16.099
So, you know, I was wondering how to like convey why this is the way it is.

00:12:16.099 --> 00:12:21.700
What I decided to do is take a few different evaluation times and do like what we would call a calibration plot.

00:12:22.099 --> 00:12:30.799
So if we had a regular classification model, what we would do, or the typical thing people do, is they take their predicted probabilities and they order the data by those probabilities.

00:12:31.099 --> 00:12:33.299
And then they come up with, let's say, 10 bins.

00:12:33.500 --> 00:12:38.500
So the highest bin is I would take samples that have probabilities from like 0.9 to 1.

00:12:38.900 --> 00:12:45.299
I would group them and actually count their actual event rate, like, you know, the mean of the zeros and ones for those data points.

00:12:45.299 --> 00:12:50.500
If my model is well calibrated, then that rate should be about the midpoint of the bin.

00:12:50.900 --> 00:12:54.900
So if I'm going like 0.9 to 1, the midpoint there is 0.95.

00:12:55.099 --> 00:12:58.500
If my model is doing well, the actual event rate should be about 0.95.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:04.299
And so you have this curve where we do it, and I did it over a couple different event times.

00:13:04.400 --> 00:13:11.700
So looking at an early time point, most of the data has a very, very high probability of being event.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.099
So the size of these points conveys how many data points are there.

00:13:16.799 --> 00:13:19.000
Remember, this had a very low Breyer score.

00:13:19.200 --> 00:13:27.700
Even though we have some points that are well off the curve, these points don't have anywhere near as much sample size as this one.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:35.299
So basically, the reason the curve is doing really well early on, because almost everything is event and they're being really easily predicted as events.

00:13:35.500 --> 00:13:40.599
And the few that are not events don't have a sample size enough to really impact that too much.

00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:44.799
And so as time went on, we saw that the Breyer score got a little bit worse.

00:13:45.099 --> 00:13:49.400
You see, we're filling out more of the probability space here, and they're not really on that line.

00:13:49.599 --> 00:13:55.200
They still are up here a fair amount, but then you're slowly starting to get more data points down here, and they're not along the line.

00:13:55.500 --> 00:13:57.799
So you can see it's like steadily getting worse.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.700
It's kind of like, I don't know, that doesn't seem that bad to me.

00:14:01.700 --> 00:14:04.599
But you can see it's just broken at 200, right?

00:14:04.599 --> 00:14:09.799
We have some that are like all over the place, and it's particularly poorly calibrated at that point.

00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:14.200
Now, this doesn't mean that it's not necessarily a poor model.

00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:17.799
If you need to get accurate probabilities, maybe this isn't the model you want.

00:14:18.099 --> 00:14:25.000
But if your goal is to differentiate who's an event and who's not an event at a specific time, then we'll see what that looks like in the RC curve.

00:14:25.099 --> 00:14:28.000
They don't always have to be matching sort of characteristic to them.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:31.299
All right.

00:14:31.700 --> 00:14:33.200
So we're probably familiar with this.

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:34.400
They are near the RC curve.

00:14:34.599 --> 00:14:36.200
The calculations are pretty straightforward.

00:14:36.200 --> 00:14:39.700
It's pretty much what we would have done before, except for incorporating these case weights.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:48.099
So when we go to calculate the sensitivity of the specificity at a particular probability threshold, we don't have like counts in the numerator or denominator.

00:14:48.299 --> 00:14:53.900
We have the total sum of the weights, the denominator, and the sum of the weights for the events in the numerator for the sensitivity.

00:14:54.200 --> 00:14:56.700
And conversely, you can imagine what we do for specificity.

00:14:57.799 --> 00:15:00.900
The reference here is this.

00:15:01.099 --> 00:15:05.500
There's a lot of references that do this inverse probability weighting, and they all do it kind of slightly different.

00:15:06.099 --> 00:15:09.500
We feel like the graph paper is like as good as it gets.

00:15:09.799 --> 00:15:20.299
So there's a lot of additional things that we do in some of the details that maybe these folks didn't do, but we apply basically the same process as we did for the prior score.

00:15:20.299 --> 00:15:24.000
We don't do a different like weighting scheme or whatever for entering the RC curve.

00:15:25.400 --> 00:15:28.000
And again, it measures separation between the events and non-events.

00:15:29.200 --> 00:15:30.799
As you might imagine, the code is pretty boring.

00:15:30.799 --> 00:15:34.299
It's RCAUC survival, same format.

00:15:34.900 --> 00:15:45.400
And then if I look at that over time, similarly, it's nearly perfect at the start and then degrades at about 200, you know, it reaches its nadir and then increases.

00:15:45.400 --> 00:15:49.799
But, you know, the end of the RC curve here is about 0.75.

00:15:49.900 --> 00:15:53.299
And I know people who would like kill to get an error in this RC curve of 0.75.

00:15:53.700 --> 00:15:58.500
So, you know, maybe this isn't bad for discrimination, even if it's not great at calibration.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.400
So there's our results for that metric.

00:16:01.500 --> 00:16:04.500
So basically the conclusion is there's good news and bad news.

00:16:04.500 --> 00:16:09.599
To me, sort of the bad news is when you evaluate these models, it's actually a pretty complicated thing.

00:16:09.599 --> 00:16:14.900
We're fitting a separate like censoring model so that we can qualify how well our model does.

00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:19.900
And if we, you know, when we eventually add informative censoring there, it's going to get even more complicated.

00:16:19.900 --> 00:16:25.000
So we have this like, you know, significant weighting scheme and have to adapt our metrics to accommodate that.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:34.700
But really, the good news is I think like most Entity Models is we can take something that's fairly complicated or like computationally intensive and give you an API that's very, very simple.

00:16:34.700 --> 00:16:43.299
If you want to do something different or if you want to look at the details, like those calibration plots I made, you have all the data that's there in the augment method.

00:16:43.299 --> 00:16:47.599
So it's not like we're obfuscating anything or preventing you from doing anything on your own.

00:16:47.599 --> 00:16:53.099
But, you know, what we want to do often in Entity Models is take something that we think is the really the right thing to do in terms of data.

00:16:53.200 --> 00:16:59.400
Even if it's really complicated, we want to give you a syntax that's that's very simple, so you don't have to like, like worry about that too.

00:16:59.400 --> 00:17:00.700
So that's pretty much it.

00:17:00.700 --> 00:17:05.900
Thanks to the group, Hannah, Mio, and Simon, who you will see more of in a minute.

00:17:05.900 --> 00:17:06.900
And thank you.

